        <h2>The History of Bhutanese Textiles</h2>
        <p>Textile production in Bhutan, initially confined to practical use, evolved into a significant cultural and artistic expression. With the support of the royal household, especially the Wangchuck dynasty rooted in Bumthang and Lhuntse District, weaving became a revered heritage art.</p>
        <p>The Wangducholing Palace, built by Trongsa Penlop Jigme Namgyal in 1857, was surrounded by loom houses known as <em>thagchem</em>, hosting dozens of skilled weavers and marking a key period in Bhutanese textile legacy.</p>
        <figure class="article-image">
          <img src="/productimage/A5.jpg" alt="An assortment of textiles from Bhutan">
          <figcaption>Handwoven masterpieces displayed at a Bhutanese textile exhibit.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Modern Revival and Royal Patronage</h2>
        <p>Princess Ashi Kencho Wangmo Wangchuck played a pivotal role in the 1930s by introducing horizontal looms from Tibet. This modernization was furthered by Her Majesty Queen Mother Ashi Sangay Choden Wangchuck, who championed textile preservation and innovation.</p>
        <p>Her Majesty’s work through the Bhutan Textile Museum and the Royal Textile Academy has brought international acclaim to Bhutanese weaving, while inspiring a new generation of textile artists.</p>
        <figure class="article-image">
          <img src="/productimage/A4.webp" alt="A Bhutanese textile">
          <figcaption>Intricate designs of a Bhutanese textile woven with spiritual symbolism.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Women Weavers</h2>
        <p>Women have always been at the heart of Bhutan’s weaving tradition. While farmers wove in spare time, royal and aristocratic households nurtured professional weavers (<em>thama</em>) who produced textiles of exceptional quality. This system created a vibrant economy centered around cloth as wealth, tax, and spiritual token.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Types of Patterns</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Plain Weaves:</strong> Typically in striped or plaid patterns.</li>
          <li><strong>Martha:</strong> Red or maroon dominant plaid design.</li>
          <li><strong>Sertha:</strong> Yellow or orange dominant plaid weave.</li>
          <li><strong>Thara:</strong> White-based horizontal striped <em>Kira</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>Kamtham Jardrima:</strong> Incorporates rainbow-striped patterns.</li>
        </ul>
